---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---
<BaseLayout title="Home" activePage="home">
  <div class="hero fade-up">
    <h1>Local LLM benchmarks on AMD Strix Halo</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">The only comprehensive multi-backend benchmark suite for gfx1151 &mdash; comparing RADV, AMDVLK, and ROCm across performance, creative writing, and coding tasks.</p>
    <span class="hardware-tag">Ryzen AI MAX+ 395 &bull; Radeon 8060S &bull; 128GB UMA &bull; RDNA 3.5</span>
  </div>

  <div class="stats-grid fade-up">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="value">b8638</div>
      <div class="label">llama.cpp build</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="value">3</div>
      <div class="label">Backends tested</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="value">26+</div>
      <div class="label">Models tested</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="value">6</div>
      <div class="label">Benchmark suites</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Latest: Gemma 4 <span class="badge new">New</span></h2>
  <p>Google's newest open models, both tested as Unsloth UD-Q4_K_XL on RADV.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap fade-up">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Model</th>
          <th>Arch</th>
          <th>Size</th>
          <th data-type="number">pp512 (t/s)</th>
          <th data-type="number">tg128 (t/s)</th>
          <th data-type="number">Writing</th>
          <th data-type="number">Coding</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td class="model-name">Gemma-4-26B-A4B</td>
          <td>MoE (4B active)</td>
          <td>16 GiB</td>
          <td class="best">1196</td>
          <td class="best">52.9</td>
          <td>23/30</td>
          <td class="best">10/10</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="model-name">Gemma-4-31B</td>
          <td>Dense</td>
          <td>17.5 GiB</td>
          <td>247</td>
          <td>11.1</td>
          <td class="best">26/30</td>
          <td class="best">10/10</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="insight fade-up">
    <p><strong>The 26B-A4B MoE is the practical pick</strong> &mdash; nearly 5x faster generation than the dense 31B, with perfect coding and solid creative writing. The 31B writes better prose but hits the same tg bottleneck as other dense models (~11 t/s).</p>
  </div>

  <div class="divider"></div>

  <h2>Polyglot Coding Gauntlet <span class="badge new">New</span></h2>
  <div class="card fade-up">
    <p>The LRU cache benchmark ran its course &mdash; 15 models score a perfect 10/10, making it useless for differentiation. Today we shipped a new polyglot coding gauntlet: seven challenges across Python, Bash, Ruby/Sinatra, and Go, totalling 65 auto-graded tests at LeetCode medium/hard difficulty. The challenges test real-world skills: parsing structured logs with nested JSON, matching cron expressions, building awk pipelines, implementing FastAPI rate-limiting middleware, writing HMAC-verified Sinatra webhook handlers, and building recursive Go rule engines.</p>
    <p>We ran every model on disk through the gauntlet. The results are humbling. <strong>Nobody breaks 22%.</strong> GPT-OSS-120B leads at 14/65, winning on bash pipelines. Qwen3-30B is right behind at 13/65 and is the only model to score on the Go rule engine (3/10) &mdash; and it did it all in 90 seconds, 40x faster than Qwen3.5-122B's 63-minute run that scored less. Three challenges remain completely unsolved across all 12 model runs: the cron matcher, the FastAPI rate limiter, and the Sinatra webhook processor.</p>
    <p>Two clear capability profiles emerged. The Qwen3 family (30B, Coder-Next, 27B dense) excels at Python regex &mdash; scoring 9&ndash;10/10 on the structured log parser &mdash; but completely fails bash extraction. GPT-OSS and the Qwen3.5 MoE family handle bash pipelines well but are weak on regex. Thinking mode actively hurts: Qwen3.5-9B jumped from 1 to 5 points when thinking was disabled, and the 122B's thinking runs timed out on multiple challenges. Model size doesn't correlate with score either &mdash; the 30B outperforms the 122B, and the Nemotron-Cascade-2's IMO gold medal reasoning scored just 1/65.</p>
    <p>We also tested whether quantization precision matters by running Gemma-4-26B-A4B at both Q4_K_XL and Q8_0. It doesn't &mdash; run-to-run variance exceeds the quant quality difference when you only have 3.8B active parameters. The benchmark is measuring model capability ceilings, not quant artifacts.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="divider"></div>

  <h2>Why this matters</h2>
  <div class="card fade-up">
    <p>AMD's Strix Halo APU pairs an RDNA 3.5 iGPU (gfx1151) with 128GB of unified memory, making it one of the most interesting platforms for running large language models locally. But benchmark data for this hardware is <strong>almost nonexistent</strong>.</p>
    <p>This site provides the missing data: head-to-head comparisons of <strong>RADV vs AMDVLK vs ROCm</strong> on identical hardware, across performance benchmarks, creative writing evaluation, and coding tasks.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Hardware</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap fade-up">
    <table>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td class="model-name">CPU</td><td>AMD Ryzen AI MAX+ 395 (16C/32T)</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="model-name">GPU</td><td>Radeon 8060S Graphics (RDNA 3.5, gfx1151)</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="model-name">Memory</td><td>128GB unified (120GB soft VRAM cap)</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="model-name">Kernel</td><td>6.17.0-8-generic</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="model-name">Vulkan</td><td>1.4.321 &mdash; Mesa RADV 25.2.3 + AMDVLK 2025.Q2.1</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="model-name">ROCm</td><td>TheRock 7.11.0a20260121 nightly</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="model-name">llama.cpp</td><td>b8638 (2026-04-02)</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2>Three backends, one GPU</h2>
  <div class="stats-grid fade-up">
    <div class="card">
      <h3>RADV</h3>
      <p>Mesa's open-source Vulkan driver. <strong>Best overall</strong> since b8119 MMQ fix. 25% pp boost on Qwen3-30B. Recommended default.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>AMDVLK</h3>
      <p>AMD's open-source Vulkan driver. Best for GPT-OSS-120B prompt processing. Good stability for production use.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>ROCm</h3>
      <p>AMD's compute stack via TheRock nightly. Requires <code>-mmp 0</code>. Best for some dense models (GLM-4.7, Qwen3.5-27B).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Explore results</h2>
  <div class="stats-grid fade-up">
    <a href={`${base}models/`} class="stat-card">
      <div class="value">26+</div>
      <div class="label">Models compared</div>
    </a>
    <a href={`${base}quantization/`} class="stat-card">
      <div class="value">AesSedai</div>
      <div class="label">vs Unsloth quants</div>
    </a>
    <a href={`${base}methodology/`} class="stat-card">
      <div class="value">65</div>
      <div class="label">Polyglot test cases</div>
    </a>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
